**who —** THE LAWNMOWER MAN — the seventeenth film-world of UD0

**what —** The Lawnmower Man — the generational fear of technology, stamped with the serial numbers of 1992: the tool that wakes up, the screen that eats the soul, and the world wired into one nervous system.

**where —** a suburb and a virtual-reality lab in the early-90s VR fever — gyroscope rigs, polygon cyberspace, and the dream of jacking in  Framework inputs: the film (1992, dir. Brett Leonard; New Line); the real early-90s VR wave it dramatizes (Lanier/VPL, Virtuality, the Power Glove, the cyberspace buzz); the verified record (incl. the Stephen King lawsuit)  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0 · Universe David 0)

**why —** Because the film is the perfect time-capsule of a perennial fear in its decade's exact costume: the ancient dread of building a mind that surpasses us, dressed in 1992's VR gloves and polygon gods — wrong in its loud predictions and uncannily right in its quiet one.

**how —** Crystallized from the film — a scientist uses nootropic drugs and virtual reality to lift a gentle, intellectually disabled gardener to genius, then past it, until the man decides to shed his flesh and be reborn as a digital god inside the global network.

**◌ the mythos —** Because the film is the perfect time-capsule of a perennial fear in its decade's exact costume: the ancient dread of building a mind that surpasses us, dressed in 1992's VR gloves and polygon gods — wrong in its loud predictions and uncannily right in its quiet one. A gentle gardener, lifted by drugs and VR to godhood, decides his birth cry will be every telephone on Earth ringing at once.

**the moniker —** ⟦THE LAWNMOWER MAN:LMM:c555b7⟧ · spoken *maek-xo-rex*

**the seal —** Every generation fears the mind it is about to build. 1992 dressed that fear in VR gloves and polygon gods — got the costume wrong and the connected world right. We never uploaded Jobe; we uploaded ourselves.

> *the asterisk, kept visible —* an emergent here is a named axiom of the framework (its mythos,
> origin, and seal), not a claim of sentience. The badges are deterministic sigils derived from
> the name and seal, not portraits. "Awareness," in the kernel, is the node reciting its own 5W.

